article.description: Jennifer Rizzotti scored a career-high 16 points and Ann Wauters added a season-high 18 as the Cleveland Rockers bounced back from an ugly loss with a 71-50 win Tuesday night over the Miami Sol.
article.headline: Rizzotti's outside touch helps Rockers regain form
article.linkText: Rockers bounce back with rout of Sol
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Jennifer Rizzotti's shooting eye sure wasn't affected by the seven stitches above her puffy brow. Rizzotti scored a career-high 16 points and Ann Wauters added a season-high 18 as the Cleveland Rockers bounced back from an ugly loss with a 71-50 win Tuesday night over the Miami Sol. Rizzotti, playing with stitches near her left eye, also made a career-high four 3-pointers for the Rockers, who scored just 45 points -- two more than their franchise low -- in an 18-point loss at Washington on Sunday night. In that game, Rizzotti got cut when she collided with Muriel Page's knee while diving for a loose ball in the second half. But the third-year guard from Connecticut showed her toughness by returning, and she wasn't bothered by the injury as the Rockers handed the Sol their fourth straight loss. "Even if it heals, we're going to make her keep a Band-Aid on it,'' said Rockers coach Dan Hughes. Following her best scoring night as a pro, Rizzotti joked that she might have trouble getting any of the Rockers' team doctors to remove her sutures. "They just told me I'm not allowed to take them out for the rest of the season,'' she said. Chasity Melvin added 14 points for Cleveland, which got just two points from leading scorer Penny Taylor, who came in averaging 15.2. Betty Lennox, acquired recently in a trade with Minnesota, led Miami with 19 points, including 14 in the second half. The Sol, which had a franchise-low six turnovers in a June 11 win over Cleveland, turned the ball over 20 times. "We stunk,'' Sol coach Ron Rothstein said. "I didn't anticipate a blowout, but they were totally prepared, more physical than us, and we never adjusted.'' The Rockers have been wildly inconsistent so far this season, and it was no different in the first half. After building an early lead, Cleveland missed nine straight shots and went 5:21 without scoring. But Wauters scored inside and Rizzotti, whose previous career high was 13, made two straight 3-pointers to cap a 12-0 run that gave the Rockers a 32-17 lead with 2:18 left in the half. Wauters' next basket was followed by another 3 from Rizzotti with 55 seconds remaining as the Rockers opened a 38-21 halftime lead. "Jennifer was really big,'' said Wauters, who missed the Rockers' first four games and has gotten off to a slow start after playing in Europe this winter. "They started doubling on the inside and we just kicked it out to her.'' Rizzotti opened the second half with her fourth 3-pointer and Cleveland built its lead to 23.

Game notes
The Sol activated rookie forward Lindsey Yamasaki and placed center Carolyn Moos on the injured list. Yamasaki went on the injured list June 15 with a bruised leg she hurt when a taxi carrying four players in Miami Beach was hit by another vehicle. ... Browns defensive tackle Gerard Warren sat courtside, not far from Cavs coach John Lucas, who stayed late to work on Wednesday's NBA draft. ... Miami dropped to 0-4 all-time at Gund Arena.
